[[Image:Runcorn soapworks.jpg|thumb|250 px|Soap and alkali works on the Bridgewater canal during the 19th century]]
During the 18th century water transport had been improved in the area by the Mersey and [[Irwell]] Navigation, the [[Bridgewater Canal]] and the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]].  This gave Runcorn waterway connections with most of the interior of England through the canal system and with the sea along the River Mersey, thus forming the basis for the development of the [[Port of Runcorn]].<ref>Starkey, ''Schooner Port'', pp.19&ndash;24 and ''Old Runcorn'', pp.125&ndash;130.</ref>  Later came the Runcorn to [[Latchford]] canal, and the Weston canal which gave better access to the Weaver Navigation system.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', p.173.</ref>  Industries began to develop within and around the town, in particular quarrying for Runcorn [[sandstone]], shipbuilding, engineering, the manufacture of soap and chemicals and tanning.  Runcorn was becoming an industrialised and highly polluted town.  During the later 19th century the town became increasingly dominated by the chemical and tanning industries.  

In 1868 the [[Runcorn Railway Bridge]] was opened across the Mersey, giving Runcorn direct rail links with [[Liverpool]] and the rest of the country.<ref>Nickson, p.206.</ref>  In the 1880s a pipeline was opened between Northwich and Weston Point, supplying brine to the salt and chemical works.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', pp.160&ndash;162.</ref>  In 1894 the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] was opened throughout its length.<ref>Starkey, ''Schooner Port'', p.184.</ref>  This allowed ocean-going ships to travel inland as far as [[Salford]], some of them calling at the port of Runcorn.  The rise in population between 1881 and 1891 and the drop by 1901 is explained by the number of people involved in constructing the ship canal.  In 1905 the [[Widnes-Runcorn Transporter Bridge]] opened, giving a direct link for vehicular traffic for the first time between the two towns.<ref>Thompson, ''Bridging the Years'', p.17.</ref>

During the first half of the 20th century the industry of the town continued to be dominated by chemicals and tanning.  In 1926 four chemical companies merged to form [[Imperial Chemical Industries]] (ICI).  As the century progressed there was diversification of industry. In 1961 the Transporter Bridge was replaced by Runcorn Road Bridge (since named the Silver Jubilee Bridge) which allowed a more efficient means of road traffic across Runcorn Gap.  The designation of Runcorn as a new town in 1964 brought major changes and more than doubled the population. Much of the architecture of the new town was innovative, especially the Southgate development designed by [[James Stirling (architect)|Sir James Stirling]] and built between 1970 and 1977.  Stirling's housing development was beset with problems and it was demolished in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=430&storycode=3084063&c=2&encCode=00000000012cb5c6 |title=Unhappy customers |accessdate=2007-07-27 |date=[[2007-03-30]] |publisher=BD: The Architects' Website}}</ref>  During the second half of the 20th century the tanneries closed and the chemical industry declined. At the same time, light industry developed together with warehouses and distribution centres.<ref name="ep">{{cite web |url=http://www.ebusinessdirectories.co.uk/BusinessDirectories/Pages/HaltonBD2006/alive.html |title=Halton Business Directory |accessdate=2007-09-01 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>

==Governance==
===Civic history===
[[Image:Halton Grange, Runcorn.jpg|thumb|left|Runcorn Town Hall, formerly Halton Grange]]
At the time of the [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] survey, Runcorn was in the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|hundred]] of Tunendune,<ref>Phillips, p.27.</ref> but later, and until the early 19th century, Runcorn was part of the Bucklow hundred.<ref>Phillips, p.9.</ref>  Under the Runcorn Improvement Act 1852, a board of [[Improvement commissioners|Improvement Commissioners]] was established to administer the civil government of the town.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', p.193.</ref>  By the [[Local Government Act 1894]], the administration of the town and the surrounding areas was divided into Runcorn [[Urban District]] and Runcorn [[Rural District]].  Initially the urban district consisted of only the built-up area of Runcorn itself.  By 1937, this area had been extended to include the communities of Weston and Weston Point to the south. By 1971 it had been further extended to the east to incorporate the village of Halton.<ref>Phillips, p.11.</ref>

In 1964, Runcorn was designated as a new town. In 1974, as part of the [[Local Government Act 1972]], Runcorn Urban District was abolished and its territory amalgamated with [[Widnes]] to form the borough of Halton.  In 1998, this borough became a [[unitary authority]] within the ceremonial county of Cheshire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/yourcouncil/theboroughofhalton?a=5441 |title=The Borough of Halton |accessdate=2007-04-23 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>

===Political representation===
Before the [[Reform Act 1832]], Runcorn was in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliamentary]] [[constituency]] of Cheshire whch was represented by two [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]].<ref>Phillips, p.100.</ref> Following the Reform Act, the town was placed in the [[North Cheshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Cheshire]] constituency and from 1868 in the [[Mid Cheshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Cheshire]] constituency.  From 1885 to 1950 the town was in the constituency of [[Northwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Northwich]].<ref>Phillips, pp.102&ndash;103.</ref>  By an [[act of Parliament]] in 1948, the [[Runcorn (UK Parliament constituency)|constituency of Runcorn]] was created, and in 1950 Runcorn's first Member of Parliament, [[Dennis Vosper, Baron Runcorn|Dennis Vosper]], was elected.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', 221.</ref> He continued to represent the constituency until 1964, when he was succeeded by [[Mark Carlisle]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2005/07/19/db1901.xml |title= Lord Carlisle of Bucklow |accessdate=2007-06-28 |date=[[2007-07-19]] |publisher=Telegraph}}</ref>  

Runcorn is part of two parliamentary constituencies.  The western part of the town, which includes the old town area and part of the new town, is in the [[Halton (UK Parliament constituency)|constituency of Halton]] and the eastern part, containing the rest of the new town and private housing to the east of this, is in the [[Weaver Vale (UK Parliament constituency)|Weaver Vale constituency]].  Since the [[United Kingdom general election, 1997|1997 general election]] the Member of Parliament for the Halton constituency has been [[Derek Twigg]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Derek+Twigg/75B0A23B-8376-4FED-B916-FE64ACF5B78B.htm |title=Derek Twigg |accessdate=2007-09-10 |publisher=ePolitix.com }}</ref> and for the Weaver Vale constituency [[Mike Hall]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Mike+Hall/5B6CB54C-57CB-4678-A8D7-F8E002B6C4B5.htm |title=Mike Hall M P |accessdate=2007-09-10 |publisher=ePolitix.com }}</ref>.  Both are members of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour party]].

The local authority is the borough of Halton. The town is divided into ten [[Ward (politics)|electoral wards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/yourcouncil/localdemocracy/?a=5441 |title=Local Democracy |accessdate=2007-03-26 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  There are 56 local councillors: 33 represent the Labour party, 15 the [[Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat party]], and 8 the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://councillors.halton.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.asp?FN=PARTY&VW=LIST&PIC=0 |title=Your councillors |accessdate=2007-07-04 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  
Runcorn is in the [[European Parliament|European parliamentary]] [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|constituency of North West England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.org.uk/uk_meps/northwest.asp |title=UK MPs for the North West |accessdate=2007-07-04 |publisher=UK Office of the European Parliament}}</ref>

==Geography==
[[Image:Runcorn Cheshire map (railways).png|thumb|280px|Sketch map of Runcorn and surrounding area]]
Runcorn is situated on a spur projecting into the River Mersey, which flows to the north and then to the west of the town. On the north bank of the river is another spur forming the West Bank area of Widnes; together these form Runcorn Gap, a narrowing of the River Mersey. Runcorn Gap is crossed by the [[Runcorn Railway Bridge]], which carries the Liverpool branch of the West Coast Main Line, and the [[Silver Jubilee Bridge]], which carries the A533 road. To the south of the town is the [[River Weaver]] and the Weston Canal. Both open into the ship canal. To the southeast of the town run the [[M56 motorway]], the [[Chester to Manchester Line|Chester–Manchester railway line]], and the main branch of the West Coast Main Line.  The town has a system of [[expressway]]s, roads designed to divert traffic away from the residential areas.<ref name="nt">{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/yourcouncil/townsandvillages/runcornnewtown?a=5441 |title=Runcorn New Town |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> The Central Expressway runs through the centre of the town in a north-south direction.  To the west of it lie most of the former settlements which formed the older part of the town, namely Runcorn, Higher Runcorn, Weston, Weston Point and Clifton (formerly Rocksavage), and the new town areas of Halton Brook and Halton Lodge.  To the east are the village of Halton, the old settlements of Norton and Stockham, and the new town areas of Castlefields, Palacefields, Windmill Hill, Murdishaw, Brookvale, and Hallwood Park.<ref>''Liverpool, St Helens, Widnes & Runcorn:Explorer 275 map'', [[Ordnance Survey]].</ref>

The density of housing is generally high, but there are open green areas, in particular [[Heath (habitat)|heathland]] on Runcorn Hill and the extensive Town Park created as part of the new town.  The older industries, particularly the remaining chemical factories, are concentrated mainly to the southwest of the town bordering the Mersey, while newer industries, including warehousing, are to the northeast and southeast.<ref name="ep"/>
[[Image:Runcorn Hill 3.jpg|thumb|left|Runcorn Hill, showing cutting through sandstone]]
===Geology===

The Runcorn area drains into the River Mersey to the north and the River Weaver to the south.  The [[bedrock]] of the western and northeastern parts of the town is made up of rock from the Sherwood [[sandstone]] group; in the other areas the bedrock is from the Mercia [[mudstone]] group. In places there are prominent [[outcrop]]s of sandstone, particularly at Runcorn Hill and Halton Hill. Elsewhere the bedrock is covered by [[drift (geology)|drift]]. At the northwestern periphery of the town the drift consists of recently blown [[sand]]. Farther to the east and bordering the River Mersey is recent [[alluvium]]. Elsewhere the drift consists of [[till]].<ref>Phillips, pp.4&ndash;5.</ref>

===Climate===
Being close to the west coast and the [[Irish Sea]], the climate is generally [[temperate]] with few extremes of temperature or weather.  The mean average temperature in the years 1971 to 2000 was 9.4 to 9.7[[Celsius|°C]], which was slightly above the average for the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/tmean/17.gif |title=Mean Temperature: Annual Average 1971&ndash;2000 |accessdate=2007-05-22 |publisher=Met Office}}</ref> as was the average amount of annual sunshine at 1391 to 1470 hours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/ss/17.gif |title=Sunshine Duration: Annual Average 1971&ndash;2000 |accessdate=2007-05-22 |publisher=Met Office}}</ref> The average annual rainfall was 741 to 870 mm, which was slightly below the average for the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/rr/17.gif |title=Rainfall Amount: Annual Average 1971&ndash;2000 |accessdate=2007-05-22 |publisher=Met Office}}</ref>  The average number of days in the year when snow is on the ground is 0 to 6, which is low for the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/dl/17.gif |title=Days of Snow Lying: Annual Average 1971&ndash;2000 |accessdate=2007-05-22 |publisher=Met Office }}</ref> The average number of days of air frost is 2 to 39, which is also low.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/daf/17.gif |title=Days of Air Frost: Annual Average 1971&ndash;2000 |accessdate=2007-05-22 |publisher=Met Office}}</ref>

==Demography==
[[Image:Castlefields Runcorn New Town.jpg|thumb|Housing in Castlefields, Runcorn New Town]]
Since the borough of Halton became a unitary authority in 1998, demographic statistics have been collated for the authority as a whole, rather than separately for the towns of Runcorn and Widnes.  While the two towns have different histories and come from different historic counties, their demographic features are similar. 

The population of Halton in 2004 was 118,915. It is the most densely populated district in Cheshire at 14.9 persons per hectare.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/yourcouncil/population?a=5441 |title=Halton Population |accessdate=2007-04-04 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> The change in population during the 20th century is shown in the following table.

