Runcorn has two shopping centres. The original shopping area was in the older part of the town on  High Street, Regent Street, and Church Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/towncentres/?a=5441 |title=Town centres |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  This centre continues to exist, but with the coming of the new town, has declined.  There is a small supermarket and some specialist shops, but with a higher-than-average proportion of charity shops and take-away food outlets.  A small market has been rebuilt adjacent to the old town bus station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/towncentres/traditionalmarkets?a=5441 |title=Markets |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  In the centre of the new town area [[Halton Lea]] (formerly Shopping City) is an enclosed [[shopping mall]] with an attached bus station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/towncentres/haltonlea?a=5441 |title=Halton Lea |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  Adjacent to it is Trident Park containing shopping outlets and a cinema and further away is an [[ASDA]] supermarket.

==Landmarks and places of interest==
[[Image:Halton Castle.jpg|thumb|Halton Castle]]
The major landmark in the town is Halton Castle on the top of Halton Hill near the geographical centre of the town. Only ruins of the castle exist, but there are widespread views from the top of the hill.  The interior of the castle grounds is open at advertised times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haltoncastle.org/ |title=The Halton Castle Website |accessdate=2007-03-27 |publisher=The Norton Priory Museum Trust}}</ref>  Incorporated in the castle walls is the Castle Hotel, which used to include a courthouse on the first floor.  Another landmark is Norton water tower, built of Runcorn sandstone, {{ft to m|112}} high, which holds 672,000&nbsp;imperial [[gallon]]s (3&nbsp;million [[litre]]s) of water and supplies water to Liverpool.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', p.162.</ref>

An important historical site and the major visitor centre in the town is Norton Priory, a museum.  The site contains the remains of an ancient priory with adjacent gardens, formerly of a country house.  Nearby are a [[walled garden]], including a national collection of tree [[quince|tree quinces]], and an [[Icehouse (building)|ice house]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rossbullock.co.uk/ |title=History of Norton Priory and Runcorn |accessdate=2007-03-27 |last=Bullock |first=Ross |date=[[2005-02-07]]}} This is a personal website but it is accurate and comprehensive. </ref><ref name="np2">{{cite web |url=http://www.nortonpriory.org/ |title=Norton Priory Museum & Gardens  |accessdate=2007-03-27 |publisher=The Norton Priory Museum Trust }}</ref>

Much of the architecture of the town is undistinguished, but there are [[Listed buildings in Runcorn, Cheshire|listed buildings]] of some importance.  The listed churches are [[All Saints Church, Runcorn|All Saints Parish Church]] and Holy Trinity Church in the centre of the older part of the town, St Mary's in Halton village, St John's in Weston, and Christ Church in Weston Point. All Saints' Church, a Grade II* listed building, dates from 1849 and was built by [[Anthony Salvin]] in red sandstone.<ref>{{cite web |title=All Saints’ Church |work=Images of England |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/search/details.aspx?pid=1&id=56027 | accessdate=2007-09-23}}</ref> The oldest existing houses are the Seneschal's house in Halton village (1598), Weston Old Hall (1607), Brookfield Farmhouse (1691), and Halton Old Hall (1693).  Other outstanding houses include Runcorn Town Hall (formerly Halton Grange), Camden House and Cottage in High Street, and Bridgewater House near the Ship Canal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/planning/forwardplanning/listedconservationareas/listedbuildings?a=5441 |title=Listed Buildings in Halton |accessdate=2007-03-27 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>

A war memorial to those who lost their lives in World War I, World War II and in later conflicts is at the bottom of Moughland Lane.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', p.218.</ref>  There is a memorial in Castle Road, Halton village, commemorating residents of the village who served in the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]].

==Culture==
===Theatre and cinema===
''[[The Brindley]]'' is a theatre and arts centre which opened in 2004.  It is situated in the old town centre and named after [[James Brindley]], engineer of the adjacent Bridgewater Canal.  It contains a [[proscenium]] theatre seating 420 and a multi-purpose theatre seating 108, ''The Studio'', which doubles as a cinema.  There is an exhibition space for art installations, a small café, and multi-purpose rooms.  The centre is owned and administered by Halton Borough Council which runs community events in the building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/thebrindley/ |title=The Brindley |accessdate=2007-07-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  In 2007 it won the title ''Best Arts Project in the UK'' at the National Lottery Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iccheshireonline.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/tm_method=full%26objectid=19819308%26siteid=50020-name_page.html |title=We did it! |accessdate=2007-09-29 |last=Breslin |first=Holly |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=[[2007-09-20]] |year= |month= |format= |work=Runcorn Weekly News |publisher=Trinity Mirror North West & North Wales Limited |pages= }}</ref>  A [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex cinema]] run by [[Cineworld]] is in Trident Park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cineworld.co.uk/reservation/ChoixResa.jgi?CINEMA=12 |title=Cineworld: Runcorn |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Cineworld Cinemas}}</ref>
[[Image:Waterloo Hotel, Runcorn.jpg|thumb|left|Waterloo Hotel, aka ''The Archer'']]

===Filmography===
Runcorn has been used for the shooting of so many films and television programmes that it has been described as ''Woollywood'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/views/liverpool-columnists/mr-brocklebank/2007/08/28/food-for-thought-64375-19699620/ |title=Food for thought |accessdate=2007-08-27 |last=Brocklebank |first=Mr |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=[[2007-08-27]] |year= |month= |format= |work= |publisher=Liverpool Daily Post |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref> combining the obvious reference to Hollywood with the dialect term [[woollyback]] sometimes used by people from Liverpool to describe those not from that city. Some of the sequences in the first two series of the [[BBC]] police drama ''[[Merseybeat (TV series)|Merseybeat]]'' were filmed in and around the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/merseybeat/ |title=Merseybeat |accessdate=2007-03-30 |publisher=BBC }}</ref> The BBC situation comedy ''[[Two Pints of Lager and a Packet of Crisps]]'' is set in Runcorn. External shots of the Waterloo Hotel in the area of High Street known as Top Locks (which is known in the show as ''The Archer'') appear as well. The opening credits show the Silver Jubilee Bridge and Halton Castle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/twopints/ |title=Two Pints of Lager & a Packet of Crisps |accessdate=2007-03-30 |publisher=BBC }} [[2007]]</ref> ''[[Drop Dead Gorgeous (TV series)|Drop Dead Gorgeous]]'', a drama on [[BBC Three]], was set in Runcorn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/programmes/gorgeous/ |title=Drop Dead Gorgeous |accessdate=2007-03-30 |publisher=BBC }}</ref> The interior of the Undercroft at Norton Priory has been used for locations in films.<ref name="np2"/>

===''The Runcorn Ferry''===
Before the building of Runcorn Railway Bridge and its attached footbridge, the only way to cross the Mersey at or near Runcorn Gap, other than by the dangerous method of fording, was by the ferry.  The ferry has a history going back to the 12th century.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', pp.10&ndash;11.</ref> The ferry was celebrated in the [[monologue]] entitled ''The Runcorn Ferry'', written by [[Marriott Edgar]] and popularised by [[Stanley Holloway]].  It includes the lines:
{{cquote|Per tuppence per person per trip…
Per trip or per part of per trip.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://monologues.co.uk/Runcorn_Ferry.htm |title=The Runcorn Ferry |accessdate=2007-05-14 |last=Edgar |first=Marriott |authorlink=Marriott Edgar |work=Make 'em Laugh!}}</ref>}}

==Community facilities==
The main library is at Halton Lea with a branch library in Egerton Street in the old town centre (which includes the archives of the Runcorn & District Historical Society).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/tourismandleisure/libraries/?a=5441 |title=Libraries |accessdate=2007-03-22 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Runcorn has two locations offering One-Stop-Shop facilities; Halton Lea Direct Link is in Halton Lea and Runcorn Direct Link is in Church Street in the old town area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/communityandliving/haltondirectlink/nearestonestopshop?a=5441 |title=One-Stop-Shop locations |accessdate=2007-05-17 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  Runcorn Direct Link also includes a [[Visitor center|Tourist Information Centre]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/tourismandleisure/tourism/touristinformationcentre?a=5441 |title=Tourist Information Centre |accessdate=2007-05-17 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>

[[Image:Runcorn Hill 2.jpg|thumb|Runcorn Hill]]
Runcorn Hill Local Nature Reserve has been developed on the site of a quarry and consists of heathland. Adjacent to it is a park which includes a bandstand, a model boating lake, and sports facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/nature/content/localnaturereserves/runcornhilllnr/ |title=Runcorn Hill Local Nature Reserve |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Wigg Island is a [[nature reserve]] on a former industrial site.  The reserve is on an island between the Manchester Ship Canal and the River Mersey and consists of open spaces and woodland with [[bird hide]]s and pathways.  Murdishaw Valley is an area of [[ancient woodland]] to the east of the town between the Murdishaw housing development and the M56.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/nature/content/localnaturereserves/wiggisland/?a=5441 |title=Wigg Island |accessdate=2007-07-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Rock Park is on the site of a quarry in the old town area and includes sports facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/parksandopenspaces/parksinhalton/rockpark/?a=5441 |title=Rock Park |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Town Park is in the centre of the new town development and has a link to the north with Norton Priory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/parksandopenspaces/?a=5441 |title=Parks, open spaces and countryside |accessdate=2007-03-22 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Open areas in Runcorn form part of Mersey Forest, one of Britain's [[Community Forests in England|community forests]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merseyforest.org.uk/ |title=The Mersey Forest Online |accessdate=2007-03-22 |publisher=The Mersey Forest Company}}</ref>

Runcorn's hospital is Halton Hospital, which is administered by the North Cheshire Hospitals NHS Trust.  This hospital is undergoing change.  Originally planned as a [[Hospital#Types|District General Hospital]], it was never large enough to provide a full range of services.  Acute medical services have been transferred to Warrington Hospital. The plan is to provide non-emergency surgery and rehabilitation at Halton Hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northcheshirehospitals.nhs.uk/ |title=The North Cheshire Hospitals NHS Trust Website |accessdate=2007-03-28 |publisher=North Cheshire Hospital NHS Trust }}</ref> Halton Haven Hospice is in the Murdishaw area of the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haltonhaven.co.uk/ |title=Halton Haven Hospice &ndash; Provider of Specialist Palliative Care|accessdate=2007-04-23 |publisher=Halton Haven Hospice}}</ref> [[Primary care]] services are provided by the Halton and St Helens [[NHS Primary Care Trust|Primary Care Trust]]. In Runcorn general practitioner services are provided in five health centres and in one separate medical practice in Heath Road.  There are dental practices providing National Health Service and private dental care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.healthcarecommission.org.uk/yourlocalhealthservices/nhsa-zbyorganisationname.cfm/widCall1/customWidgets.content_view_1/cit_id/4473 |title=Halton & St. Helens Primary Care Trust |accessdate=2007-09-01 |publisher=Healthcare Commission}}</ref>

==Transport== 
[[Image:Runcorn Bridges.jpg|thumb|left|Runcorn railway bridge is on the left and Silver Jubilee (road) bridge on the right]]
There are two railway stations.  [[Runcorn railway station|Runcorn (mainline) station]] is on the Liverpool branch of the West Coast Main Line.  From this station, [[Virgin Trains]] run 15 trains daily on weekdays between Liverpool and London, and [[London Midland]] run services between Liverpool and Birmingham.  [[Runcorn East railway station|Runcorn East station]] is on the Chester to Manchester line.  [[Arriva Trains Wales]] and [[Northern Rail]] run an hourly service to Chester, Warrington, and Manchester.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/publictransport/content/railinformation/?a=5441 |title=Rail Information |accessdate=2007-03-21 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>

[[Bus rapid transit#Implementation in Europe|Busways]] are also available. These are for use by buses only.<ref name="nt"/> There are two bus stations, one in the old town centre and the other at Halton Lea.  Two companies provide local public transport services, [[Halton Transport]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haltontransport.co.uk/ |title=Halton Transport |accessdate=2007-07-28 |publisher=Halton Borough Transport Ltd}}</ref> and [[Arriva North West and Wales|Arriva]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arrivabus.co.uk/__80256E280053B5B6.nsf/vWeb/pcCWAN5XFEHA?open&region=North%20West%20and%20Wales&town=Runcorn&service= |title=Arriva bus timetable for Runcorn |accessdate=2007-09-01 |publisher=Arriva plc }}</ref>  Express coach services calling at Runcorn are provided between Hoylake via Liverpool and London and between Southport and Cambridge by [[National Express]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/publictransport/content/businformation/?a=5441 |title=Bus Information |accessdate=2007-03-21 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Coach services are provided by Selwyns<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.selwyns.co.uk/index.html |title=Selwyns Transport Solutions |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Selwyns Travel Ltd}}</ref> and Anthony's Travel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anthonys-travel.co.uk/ |title=Anthony's Travel |accessdate=2007-06-28 |publisher=Anthony's Travel }}</ref> Both companies have depots in the town.

Runcorn has a system of expressways diverting through traffic from the local roads.<ref name="nt"/>  This system links to the north by the A533 over the Silver Jubilee Bridge to Widnes and south Lancashire, to the northeast to Warrington by the [[A56 road|A56]], to the east to [[Northwich]] and north Cheshire by the A533, and to the southeast by the A557 to the [[M56 motorway|M56]] and to [[Frodsham]].  The M56 links to the [[M6 motorway|M6]] and, to the north of Widnes, the A557 links to the [[M62 motorway|M62]].<ref>''Landranger'' 108, 109 and 117 maps, [[Ordnance Survey]]</ref> The Silver Jubilee Bridge becomes congested at peak travel times. In the event of a breakdown or accident on the bridge, traffic in the area comes to a standstill.  To resolve this problem, a second crossing of the Mersey is planned, to be known as the ''Mersey Gateway''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/merseygateway/ |title=The Mersey Gateway |accessdate=2007-03-26 |publisher=Mersey Gateway Project }}</ref> There is a network of dedicated [[Segregated cycle facilities|cycleways]] in the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/publictransport/content/cycling/?a=5441 |title=Cycling in Halton |accessdate=2007-03-29 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>  Runcorn is {{mi to km|8}} from [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport]] and {{mi to km|22}} from [[Manchester Airport]].

==Education==
There are 29 [[primary school]]s in the town and one [[nursery school]] at The Grange. The four [[secondary education#United Kingdom|secondary schools]] are Halton High, St. Chad's Catholic High, The Grange, and [[The Heath School|The Heath]].  Two institutions, Halton College and Runcorn Sixth Form College, merged in 2006 to form the Riverside College Halton.  There is one [[special school]] in the town, Cavendish School.  There are opportunities for [[adult education]] in [[information technology]] at the Acorn Lifelong Learning Centre and at the Grange City Learning Centre.  Other courses for adults are held at different venues in the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/educationandlearning/?a=5441 |title=Education and learning |accessdate=2007-03-30 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>[[Image:StChadsRuncorn.jpg|thumb|150px|St Chads Catholic High School]]

The achievement and attainment tables for 2006 show that the primary schools in the Halton Local Authority perform in English, mathematics, and science in [[Key Stage 2]] at levels close to the average for England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/group_06.pl?Mode=Z&No=876&Base=p&Type=LA&Phase=p&Year=06 |title=Primary School (Key Stage 2) Achievement and Attainment Tables 2006 |accessdate=2007-07-04 |publisher=Department for Children, Schools and Families}}</ref>  The attainments of the secondary schools in the local authority are more variable.  For 2006, using the measure of 5 or more grades A*&ndash;C in the [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] (or equivalent), the average for England was 59.2% while the Halton average was 52.6%.  The figures for the individual secondary schools in Runcorn were Halton High 52%, The Grange 36%, The Heath 72% and St. Chad's Catholic High 50%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/group_06.pl?Mode=Z&No=876&Base=b&Type=LA&Phase=1&Year=06 |title=Secondary School (GCSE and equivalent) Achievement and Attainment Tables 2006 |accessdate=2007-07-04 |publisher=Department for Children, Schools and Families }}</ref>  In 2007 the figure for Halton Local Authority rose to 61.1%.  The increase of 8.5% over the previous year is the greatest percentage increase in England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iccheshireonline.icnetwork.co.uk/runcorn-widnes/news/tm_method=full%26objectid=20001940%26siteid=50020-name_page.html |title=Halton applauded for GCSE improvements |accessdate=2007-10-26 |last=Hopkins |first=Rob |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=[[2007-10-25]] |year= |month= |format= |work=Runcorn and Widnes Weekly News |publisher=Trinity Mirror North West & North Wales Limited  |pages= }}</ref>  For individual schools the figures include St. Chad's Catholic High 56%,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.st-chads.co.uk/index.html |title=St Chads Welcome Back News |accessdate=2007-09-07 |publisher=St Chads Catholic High School }}</ref> The Heath School 83%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heath.halton.gateway.talmos.net/pages/viewpage.asp?uniqid=37&blockid=1344 |title= 	
Record results at The Heath |accessdate=2007-09-07 |publisher=The Heath School }}</ref>

==Religion==
[[Image:Runcorn All Saints 1.jpg|thumb|150px|[[All Saints Church, Runcorn|All Saints Parish Church]]]]
The 2001 [[census]] showed, that of the people living in the borough of Halton, 83.8% declared themselves to be [[Christian]], 8.7% stated that they had "no religion," and 7.0% made no religious claims at all. Those stating their religions as [[Buddhism|Buddhist]], [[Hinduism|Hindu]], [[Judaism|Jewish]], [[Islam]] or [[Sikhism|Sikh]] amounted to 0.5%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/Product.asp?vlnk=12640&More=Y |title=Religion, Census 2001: Key Statistics for the rural and urban area classification |accessdate=2007-04-02 |publisher=Office for National Statistics }}</ref>

The [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] churches are part of the [[Diocese of Chester]] and the deanery of Frodsham.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chester.anglican.org/diocese/links/index.htm#Frodsham |title=Chester Diocese:Frodsham Deanery |accessdate=2007-04-02 |publisher=The Church of England: Diocese of Chester }}</ref><ref name="church">{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/localinfo/placesofworship/churchesinruncorn/?a=5441 |title=Churches in Runcorn |accessdate=2007-04-02 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref>
In Runcorn, the parish church is All Saints in the old town centre. Ten other Anglican churches are in the town.<ref name="church"/>  Five Roman Catholic churches can be found in Runcorn and are administered by the [[Diocese of Shrewsbury]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dioceseofshrewsbury.org/ |title=The Diocese of Shrewsbury |accessdate=2007-04-04 |publisher=The Roman Catholic Diocese of Shrewsbry }}</ref>  There are three Methodist chapels and one [[Presbyterian Church of Wales|Welsh Presbyterian]] chapel.  Wicksten Drive Christian Centre is shared between the Church of England and the Methodists.  Hallwood Ecumenical Parish in Beechwood and Palace Fields consists of 3 churches all recognised by the Church of England, the Methodists and the [[United Reformed Church]]. Norton Ecumenical Parish, covering Windmill Hill, Norton and Murdishaw, is served by an Ecumenical Partnership between St Berteline's Church (Anglican) and Murdishaw Ecumenical Church (Methodist run).

There is an [[Independent Baptist]] chapel, three independent Christian churches, and a [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].   The [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] have two [[Kingdom Hall]]s, and there is a [[Spiritualism|Spiritualist]] church.<ref name="church"/>  There are no places of worship in Runcorn for any other major world religions.

==Sports==
Runcorn's main football club is [[Runcorn Linnets|Runcorn Linnets FC]]. This club has had a complicated history.  At one time, Runcorn F. C. played on a ground in Canal Street, Runcorn.  When this land was sold for housing in 2000, the team played at grounds outside the town and it was renamed [[Runcorn F.C. Halton]].  In 2006 there was a change of management, and the team's name was changed again. At the end of the 2006&ndash;07 season, the club gained promotion from Division 2 to Division 1 of the [[North West Counties Football League|North West Counties League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.runcornfc.co.uk/ |title=Runcorn Linnets FC |accessdate=2007-09-01 |publisher=Runcorn Linnets FC Trust }}</ref> It is hoped that they will be able to play their home games in Runcorn starting in the 2007&ndash;08 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Linnets aim for new home after promotion | date =[[April 26]] [[2007]] | first = Dave |last=Bettley | work= Runcorn Weekly News |publisher=icCheshireOnline |url = http://iccheshireonline.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/runcornandwidnesweeklynews/tm_method=full%26objectid=18970107%26siteid=50020-name_page.html| accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref>  There are a number of smaller football clubs in the town for adults and children.

Runcorn Cricket Club and Runcorn Hockey Club are based at the Runcorn Sports Club in Moughland Lane.  Runcorn Rugby Union FC is based at Halton Sports Club in Murdishaw.  There is an 18 hole golf course at Runcorn Golf Club in Clifton Road<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk/cheshire/runcorn.php |title=Runcorn Golf Club |accessdate=2007-04-25 |publisher=English Golf Courses}}</ref> and a golf driving range at Sutton Fields.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suttonfields.co.uk/index.html |title=Sutton Fields |accessdate=2007-03-29 |publisher=Sutton Fields }}</ref>  Runcorn Sports Club is a privately run sports club in Moughland Lane and provides facilities and coaching for cricket and hockey. Halton Sports Club is in Murdishaw Avenue. Privately run swimming pools are at Beechwood local centre and Stockham Lodge Raquet and Health Club. Adjacent to the latter are two [[artificial ski slope]]s administered by Runcorn Ski Centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.runcornskicentre.co.uk/ |title=Runcorn Ski Centre |accessdate=2007-03-29 |publisher=Runcorn Ski Centre }}</ref> The Runcorn Rowing Club rows on the River Weaver Navigation near Clifton Village.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.runcornrowing.com/ |title=Runcorn Rowing Club |accessdate=2007-03-29 |publisher=Runcorn Rowing Club }}</ref> The local authority runs several sports centres, including: Runcorn Swimming Pool; Brookvale Recreation Centre, offering indoor sporting facilities; and Phoenix Park, with outdoor sporting facilities. Other sports are also catered for.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/tourismandleisure/sports?a=5441 |title=Sports in Halton |accessdate=2007-03-29 |publisher=Halton Borough Council}}</ref> Runcorn has a professional wrestling academy, the Runcorn Wrestling Academy (RWA).

==Notable people==
[[Image:Thomas Hazlehurst.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Thomas Hazlehurst,<br> chapel builder]]
Individuals from Runcorn who have gained entry into the [[Dictionary of National Biography#Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'']] include [[Sir John Chesshyre]] (1662&ndash;1738), a prominent lawyer,<ref>Lemmings, David (2004) 'Chesshyre, Sir John (1662&ndash;1738)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, online edn[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5235]. Retrieved on [[7 March]] [[2007]]</ref>   [[Nathan Alcock]] (1707&ndash;79), a noted physician,<ref>Moore, Norman (2004) ‘Alcock, Nathan (1709–1779)’, rev. Caroline Overy, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, online edn. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/292]. Retrieved on [[1 March]] [[2007]]</ref> and his brother  [[Thomas Alcock (1709-1798)|Rev. Thomas Alcock]] (1709&ndash;98), Vicar of Runcorn, and writer and [[cider]] maker.<ref>Woodland, Patrick (2004) ‘Alcock, Thomas (1709&ndash;1798)’, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, online edn, [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/296]. Retrieved on [[1 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  [[Thomas Hazlehurst (businessman)|Thomas Hazlehurst]] (1779&ndash;1842) founded one of the two major soap and alkali manufacturing businesses in the town, [[Hazlehurst & Sons]].  His son [[Thomas Hazlehurst (chapel builder)|Thomas Hazlehurst]] (1816&ndash;76) was involved with the business. He was a [[Methodist]] who paid for the construction of 12 chapels and three schools in the area.<ref> Vardy, P. I. (2005-2006) 'Thomas Hazlehurst and his family', ''Cheshire History'', 45.</ref>  

[[Edward John Smith]] (1850&ndash;1912), captain of the ''[[RMS Titanic|Titanic]]'',  purchased a retirement home in Higher Runcorn but never lived there because of his death aboard the Titanic. [[Hall Caine|Thomas Henry Hall Caine]] (1853&ndash;76), a novelist and playwright, was born in Runcorn.<ref>Allen, Vivien (1997) ''Hall Caine: Portrait of a Victorian Romancer'', Sheffield Academic Press, ISBN 1-85075-809-3</ref>  [[Thomas Alfred Jones]] (1880&ndash;56) was awarded the [[Victoria Cross]] and the [[Distinguished Conduct Medal]] during World War I.<ref>Thompson, Dave (2002) ''I Laughed Like Blazes: The Life of Private Thomas 'Todger' Jones, VC, DCM'' Dave Thompson.</ref>  In more recent times the singer and actress [[Kym Marsh]] (1976&ndash; ) and her actor husband [[Jack Ryder (actor)|Jack Ryder]] (1981&ndash; ) often spend their weekends in Runcorn with Marsh's family.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iccheshireonline.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/tm_objectid=17001927&method=full&siteid=50020&headline=ex-hear-say-star-s-passion-for-runcorn--name_page.html |title=Ex Hear'Say star's passion for Runcorn |accessdate=2006-11-12 |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=[[2006-04-27]] |year= |month= |format= |work=Runcorn Weekly News |publisher=icCheshireOnline |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>  The boxer [[Robin Reid]] (1971&ndash; ) attended secondary school in Runcorn, a place he identifies as his home town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=5000&cat=boxer |title=Boxer: Robin Reid |accessdate=2007-04-23 |publisher=BoxRec}}</ref> The singer [[Nicola Roberts]] (1985&ndash; ) from the British girl band, '[[Girls Aloud]],' also comes from Runcorn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nicolaroberts.net/page3/page3.html |title=About Nicola |accessdate=2007-04-23 |publisher=Nicola Roberts [dot net]}}</ref>

